  The only way to make tradeskills more valueable would be to make it harder and harder to be a grandmaster.  <br>
<br>
example QAT...I too will be selling and giving away the stuff soon.  I decided to learn brewing.  Although I have not tracked it closely I have not spent more then 200 plat to get my skill to 140.  It took me about 8 hours of real time over three days.  I have all the items I need to raise my skill up to 160.(once my wrists recover).  I have enough compoents to make about 1000 QAT in my bank...Now I do not know the fail rate at a skill of 160, nor do I know the cost...(I really intend to grandmaster tailoring, I may find the QAT fail rate too high even at 199, in which case you will have another customer(me)).<br>
   man I am rambling...the point was it is not that hard to run up a given skill.  Since there are no real life controls. A true grandmaster tradeperson is limited by their real talent.  IN EQ people are not limited by their god given talents, It is a formula.  So what will limit it?  Only supply will limit it.  If a market is flooded store your stock...stop producing...do not sell, or take a break from producing more.  Do not take part in a price war with some boob who is selling too low.  You know your true cost, stick to it.  If Some gomer is selling below cost, take a break, let him loose the money.  He will get tired and stop...or run out of money...then you can put out your shingle again.  All tradeskills that have a consumeable item as the product will eventually stablelize at an profitable price.  Unlike real life time is on your side.  You never go out of business for lack of customers...they cannot win a price war.  now gratned going through the cycle 150 times is little fun, but you will always win.  An alternate path might be to take the product to the customer...visit the zone where people are likly to be, and have the level to have the money to meet your price.  There are too many sellers in the Bazaar.  Take a duffle bag full to rathe mountians and sell to the giant hunting parties...I bet they would buy(after you told them what it is).<br>
<br>
