er intended tradeskills to be used in that way, is completely irrelevant.  The facts come down to one simple thing; numbers.   Lets look at some numbers..<br>
<br>
Star ruby encrusted stein: cost to make at 200 skill 300pp, cost to make at 250 skill 70 - 140 plat.  Time to make: 20 minutes to get components for 20 attempts, so ~1 minute per unit.  Standard price the GM potters are selling it for in bazaar? 1200 (down from old monopoly price of 2k+<br>
<br>
Opal encrusted stein, cost to make at 200 skill 20 plat, cost to make at 250 skill 20 plat.  Time to make: same as Star Ruby Stein above.  Price potters are selling for in bazaar = 75 plat, down from old monopoly price of 250.<br>
<br>
Grobb liquidized meat, cost to make at 170 skill 60 plat per stack, cost to make at 250 skill 30 plat per stack.  Time to make: 15-30 min to prep materials for 20 attempts, which yields 6 full stacks of product (so ~3 min per stack).  Price GM brewers selling in bazaar = 200 plat/stack.<br>
<br>
Demi-sec champagne, cost to make at 200 skill 50 plat, cost to make at 250 skill 30 plat.  Time to make: 45 seconds.  Selling price in Bazaar ~200 plat (down from old price of 500 - 1k+)<br>
<br>
Blessed Fishing Pole, cost to make at 200 skill 125 - 500 plat depending if you can forage or not.  Time to make: 30-60 minutes if you forage components yourself, 15 minutes if you buy them in Bazaar; priced accordingly as above.  Price in bazaar 1500 - 2500 plat.<br>
<br>
Note these are just some examples.   Also note that I specifically focused on items which are purely store-bought components (except for the pole, which has easily obtainable parts).   Because they are storebought, there is absolute clarity on the cost to make; the cost is that which the vendor charges, and is not based to market fluctuation of &quot;farmed&quot; components.  These prices are not second hand, they are based upon my personal tradeskill experience.   Why do I put my time into tradeskills?  Because I don't like seeing my friends and my guild buying things that are marked up at a 500%+ profit margin.  Jewelery craft has always been a tradeskill which sells at about a 1.5 - 2.0 markup.   So why is it people feel it is acceptable to do a 5.0 - 10.0 markup on the other tradeskills?   Can you imagine if someone tried to charge 6k plat a pair for Velium fire opal rings instead of 800 plat a pair?   People would cry bloody murder.  I would love to hear someone explain to me and the rest of the world how Jewelery Craft pricing is any different from the pricing examples I used above.  <br>
<br>
EDIT: Removed Robe from the example list above, the pricing on it is too volatile (due to wild variance in the success/fail on chain) to allow for a fair &quot;average&quot; price listing.  Also, in response to Dorphen below, it should be noted that these costs are only materials, they don't include time in making the item or time in getting the skill up to the point where you can make attempts as per above.  HOWEVER, even with a very fair price markup included over cost of materials (to cover time/etc) my original point still stands that some of the prices people charge are quite simply wrong, obscene, disgusting, etc etc.  Example:  Grobb Liquid meat, while low cost per unit to make and is entirely storebought, does require time to make (multiple sub-combines leading up to final combine).  The final combine produces 6 units however, and making mass quantities of the stuff is relatively simple/inexpensive, if a bit tedious.<br>
<br>
Also added &quot;time to make&quot;, for the sake of completeness. <p><br>Azhrei Hiever d'Phlith, 59th Enforcer of Innoruuk's Word
